Q: Shape intersection design A: <p>Here is a proposal: you might rely on a <code>Intersector</code> struct checking that we can have only one <code>intersect</code> overload for (A,B) or (B,A), ie. we have a <code>xor</code> test to proceed.
If the assertion is ok, we use a <code>constexpr</code> test in order to call the actual <code>intersect</code> overload:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>struct Intersector {
    template&lt;typename A, typename B&gt;
    bool operator() (A const&amp; a, B const&amp; b)  const {

        static_assert (has_intersect&lt;A,B&gt;::value  xor has_intersect&lt;B,A&gt;::value);

        if constexpr (has_intersect&lt;A,B&gt;::value)  { return intersect(a,b); }
        else                                      { return intersect(b,a); }
    }
};
</code></pre>
<p>Here, <code>has_intersect</code> is defined as follows (no concepts with c++17, so we go the old way, see <a href="https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/void_t.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">here</a> for instance)</p>
<pre><code>template&lt;class A, class B, class = void&gt;
struct has_intersect : std::false_type{};

template&lt;class A,class B&gt;
struct has_intersect&lt;A,B, typename std::void_t&lt;decltype(intersect(std::declval&lt;A&gt;(),std::declval&lt;B&gt;()))&gt;&gt; : std::true_type{};
</code></pre>
<p>Finally, we can use it for instance like this</p>
<pre><code>//bool intersect (Triangle const&amp;, Circle   const&amp;)  { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;triangle/circle\n&quot;; return true; }
bool intersect (Circle const&amp;,   Triangle const&amp;)  { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;circle/triangle\n&quot;; return true; }

int main() {
    Intersector inter;
    inter (Triangle(), Circle());
}
</code></pre>
